.TH HSH 1 "April 2026" "1.0" "Simple Shell Manual"
.SH NAME
hsh \- simple UNIX command interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
[\fIscript_file\fR] [\fIargument ...\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX command language interpreter that executes commands read
from standard input or from a file.
.PP
The shell reads commands either interactively from the user's terminal or
non-interactively from a file. It parses the input, resolves command paths,
and executes the appropriate program using the environment inherited from the
parent process.
.SH INVOCATION
.SS Interactive mode
When invoked with standard input connected to a terminal, the shell displays
a prompt
.RB ( $ )
and waits for the user to enter a command.
.PP
.nf
$ ./hsh
$ /bin/ls
hsh main.c shell.c
$ exit
.fi
.SS Non\-interactive mode
When input is not connected to a terminal, the shell reads commands from
standard input line by line without displaying a prompt.
.PP
.nf
$ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
hsh main.c shell.c
.fi
.SH BUILT-IN COMMANDS
.TP
.B exit \fR[\fIn\fR]
Exit the shell. If \fIn\fR is provided, it is used as the exit status;
otherwise the exit status of the last command is used.
.TP
.B env
Print the current environment to standard output. Each environment variable
is printed on its own line in the form \fINAME=value\fR.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.B hsh
exits with the exit status of the last command executed. If a command is not
found, the exit status is
.BR 127 .
If a command is found but cannot be executed, the exit status is
.BR 126 .
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B PATH
A colon-separated list of directories in which the shell looks for commands.
.TP
.B HOME
The home directory of the current user.
